PROJECT_DESCRIPTION:
The Old Colony region is experiencing a critical need for sustainable access to diversified, resilient water resources. Job creation is being stunted in municipalities like Avon where business and industrial parks have no or limited access to public water supply. Several municipalities are also facing uncertainty about their once perceived as abundant water supplies; for example, Plymouth is currently studying the threat saltwater intrusion caused by rising a sea-level may pose to their Sole Source Aquifer. Brockton, meanwhile, is considering additional supply side options as their primary source of water, Silver Lake, is deteriorating in quality, susceptible to drought, and overused to the point of impacting the ecological integrity of the local area.

OCPC is leading an inclusive planning process to develop a regional water plan for our region, which includes the thirteen communities of the Upper Taunton River Watershed plus four others to the east (Hanover, Duxbury, Kingston, and Plymouth). These four communities are connected to the Upper Taunton River Watershed through the manmade water supply system tied to Silver Lake.

This project will:
1. Develop a baseline understanding of water use in each municipality and across the region;
2. Review models, where they exist, and develop a new model, if necessary, to project future demand in each municipality and across the region;
3. Determine whether future demand can be met affordably and sustainably with current water supplies in the context of a changing climate;
4. Identify new supply-side options and analyze the economic, social, and environmental costs and benefits of developing those options;
5. Identify good water resources management practices needed, including water demand management measures, water reuse, etc.
